<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-818-900  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 818 900.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Sept 1990 v27 n9 p46(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The technical ladder gets harder to climb: lean times areaffecting the corporate technical ladder, and engineers arelearning to take personal initiative to make it work. (includesrelated article on career ladders)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Youst, David B.; Lipsett, Laurence.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many companies offer engineers two main career paths foradvancement, either technical or managerial.andP;  With layoffs andcorporate mergers being commonplace, it is important for engineersadvancing on the technical ladder to understand its use for theircareer advancement and personal growth.andP;  A typical technicalladder consists of an entry level engineer moving up through theranks to a group leader/project supervisor, member of technicalstaff, senior member of technical staff, engineering fellow andsenior engineering fellow.andP;  Technical expertise, while veryimportant, is not enough to ensure career advancement.andP;  Inteamwork situations, effective communication and persuasion skillsneed to be developed along with the ability to cope with thepressure to complete more projects while keeping up with rapidlychanging technical information.andP;  Engineers must take theinitiative to create a successful career.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Career DevelopmentEngineeringEmployment Opportunity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>